            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17861025-109-person1330">
                  BENJAMIN
                   COOMBES
               <interp inst="t17861025-109-person1330" type="surname" value="COOMBES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17861025-109-person1330" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17861025-109-person1330" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I am a <rs id="t17861025-109-viclabel605" type="occupation">carpenter</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17861025-109-victim1329 t17861025-109-viclabel605"></join>; I lost my watch on Sunday was se'night, from one <placeName id="t17861025-109-crimeloc606">Buer's in Chandos-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t17861025-109-crimeloc606" type="placeName" value="Buer's in Chandos-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t17861025-109-crimeloc606" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17861025-109-off603 t17861025-109-crimeloc606"></join>; the prisoner did take my watch; I went into Duke's-court in the morning and had a pint of purl, and from that time we went home to my lodgings, there he sent for a quartern of gin; I drank one glass and he another, and the landlord another; then he asked me to go to bowls, and I sit down on the bench, and laid my head down on the table.</p>
               <p>You was in liquor I suppose? - No, he asked me what o'clock it was; I did not make him any answer; he took the<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="178610250191"></xptr> watch out of my pocket, and went off with it, between eleven and twelve at noon.</p>
               <p>How soon did he go off? - In about twenty minutes, or it might be less.</p>
               <p>How came you to let him go off with your watch? - I thought he would give it me again; he lodged in Little Moore's-yard; the same place that I do; I went home the night I lost my watch, but he did not come that night; I found him at home, and in bed; I asked him for my watch he had taken out of my pocket; he said, he had no such thing; I asked him twice whether he would deliver up the watch he had taken from me; he said, he did not know any thing at all about it; I took him to the watch-house; I never got my watch again.</p>
               <p>Do you say you was not in liquor? - No, I was very bad in my head.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17861025-109-person1331">
                  MARY
                   SILCOCK
               <interp inst="t17861025-109-person1331" type="surname" value="SILCOCK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17861025-109-person1331" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17861025-109-person1331" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I have known the prisoner eight years since the Westminster association, he asked me a little trifle for rent; I went to him and asked him to settle it; he told me he would be with me on Saturday night or Sunday; on the Sunday evening he came between four and five; he was very much toxicated in liquor; says he, I cannot pay you, then says he, I am doing very well, I have got my watch out of pawn; and he had a silver watch in his hand; I knew him eight years ago to have a watch; he went away; I thought this was the prisoner's watch; I never knew the prisoner guilty of any improper action; he is a hard working industrious man.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I knew nothing at all about the matter till I was challenged about it on Monday night to my knowledge; I have not had a watch for some weeks; I have worked hard upon the spot seven or eight years; I never saw any watch; if I had been guilty of such a thing as this, many favourable opportunities would have happened; I had no watch to my knowledge.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17861025-109-verdict607" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17861025-109-verdict607" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               NOT GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>Tried by the first Middlesex Jury before Mr. 
